- RW (white eyes)
- WR (white eyes)
- WW (white eyes)

Eyes look white for RW, WR, and WW, which occur with a combined probability of 3/4. The event of having two white alleles (WW) occurs with probability 1/4.

Given that the eyes look white (event B), the conditional probability of having two white alleles (event A) is:
P(A|B) = P(A and B) / P(B)

Since WW implies white eyes, P(A and B) = P(WW) = 1/4. P(B) = P(white eyes) = 3/4. Thus:
