Problem: 5.3-19. Two components operate in parallel in a device, so the device fails when and only when both components fail. The lifetimes, $X_1$ and $X_2$, of the respective components are independent and identically distributed with an exponential distribution with $\theta=2$. The cost of operating the device is $Z=2 Y_1+Y_2$, where $Y_1=\min \left(X_1, X_2\right)$ and $Y_2=\max \left(X_1, X_2\right)$. Compute $E(Z)$.
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The lifetimes \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) are independent and identically distributed exponential random variables with mean \(\theta = 2\), so the rate parameter is \(\lambda = 1/2\).

The cost is defined as \(Z = 2Y_1 + Y_2\), where \(Y_1 = \min(X_1, X_2)\) and \(Y_2 = \max(X_1, X_2)\). The expected value is \(E(Z) = 2E(Y_1) + E(Y_2)\).

For two independent exponential random variables with rate \(\lambda\), the minimum \(Y_1\) follows an exponential distribution with rate \(2\lambda\). Thus, \(E(Y_1) = 1/(2\lambda)\). Substituting \(\lambda = 1/2\) gives \(E(Y_1) = 1/(2 \times 1/2) = 1/1 = 1\).

The expected value of the maximum \(Y_2\) is given by \(E(Y_2) = 3/(2\lambda)\). Substituting \(\lambda = 1/2\) gives \(E(Y_2) = 3/(2 \times 1/2) = 3/1 = 3\).

Therefore, \(E(Z) = 2 \times 1 + 3 = 5\).

The result is exact and does not require rounding.

